<subsection xml:id="subsec-properties-of-rotation" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
    <title>Properties of Rotation</title>
    <objectives component="outcomes">
        <introduction>
            <p>
            <dl>
                <li>
                    <title>Strand</title>
                    <p>
                        2.0 Measurements and Geometry
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <title>Sub-Strand</title>
                    <p>
                        2.3 Rotation
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <title>Specific Learning Outcomes</title>
                    <p>
                        Determine the properties of rotation in different situations
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li component="lesson-plan">
                    <title>Grade Level</title>
                    <p>
                        10
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li component="lesson-plan">
                    <title>Estimated Duration</title>
                    <p>
                        40 minutes
                    </p>
                </li>
            </dl>
            </p>
            <p component="lesson-plan">
                <p> Upon completion of this lesson, learners will be able to:
                <ol>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <alert>Know (Conceptual Understanding):</alert> Define rotation as a transformation that turns an object through an angle about a fixed point (centre of rotation). Identify the centre, angle, and direction (clockwise/anticlockwise) of rotation. State the key properties: distances from centre are preserved, angle of rotation is constant for all points, and shape and size are preserved.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <alert>Do (Procedural Skill):</alert> Identify the centre and angle of rotation given an object and its image. Determine the properties of rotation by examining object-image pairs. Apply rotation rules (<m>90°</m>, <m>180°</m>, <m>270°</m>) on the Cartesian plane.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <alert>Apply (Application/Problem-Solving):</alert> Apply properties of rotation to solve geometric problems. Recognise rotation in real-world contexts (clock hands, wheels, doors). Use rotation to create symmetric patterns.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
                </p>
            </p>
        </introduction>
    </objectives>
        <axiom component="resources">
        <!-- Link to blurb -->
        <xi:include href="../../resources-blurb-lesson.ptx" />

        <sbsgroup widths="45% 45%" margins="2% 2%">
            <sidebyside>
                <p>
                    <dataurl source="lesson_plans/measurements-and-geometry/rotation/properties-of-rotation.pdf"> Lesson Plan </dataurl>
                </p>
                <p>
                    <dataurl source="lesson_plans/measurements-and-geometry/rotation/step-by-step-guide_properties-of-rotation.pdf"> Step-by-Step Guide </dataurl>
                </p>
            </sidebyside>
        </sbsgroup>
    </axiom>
    <xi:include href="../../resources-materials.ptx" />

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Exploring Properties of Rotation</title>
        <dl>
            <li>
                <title>Suggested Time</title>
                <p>
                    15 minutes
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <title>Grouping</title>
                <p>
                    Groups
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <title>Setup</title>
                <p>
                    Square on Cartesian plane: <m>A(2,2)</m>, <m>B(4,2)</m>, <m>C(4,4)</m>, <m>D(2,4)</m>, centre <m>O(0,0)</m>.
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <title>Steps</title>
                <p>
                    <ol marker="(a)">
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                Plot square, rotate <m>90°</m> anticlockwise <mdash/> <m>A \to A'(-2,2)</m>, <m>B \to B'(-2,4)</m>, <m>C \to C'(-4,4)</m>, <m>D \to D'(-4,2)</m>.
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                Measure <m>OA</m>, <m>OA'</m>, <m>OB</m>, <m>OB'</m>.
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                Compare: shape, size, distances from <m>O</m>, angles.
                            </p>
                        </li>
                    </ol>
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <title>Teacher's Role</title>
                <p>
                    Circulate among groups, asking probing questions: <q>What stays the same?</q>, <q>What changes?</q>, <q>What about <m>180°</m>?</q>, <q>Different centre?</q> Expected answers: distances preserved, shape preserved, angle same for all points, only position changes.
                </p>
            </li>
        </dl>
    </axiom>

    <introduction xml:id="auto_m06sgpg3">
         <activity xml:id="auto_vssxe3xn">
            <introduction xml:id="auto_kbgshok4">
                <p xml:id="auto_3g8fafy2">
                    <alert>Work in pairs</alert>
                </p>

                <p xml:id="auto_q7vj0d0e">
                     <m>\textbf{What you need:}</m> Graph paper, a ruler, a protractor and a pencil.
                </p>
            </introduction>
            <task xml:id="auto_rddma22m">
                <statement>
                    <p xml:id="auto_j1ur6ts0">
                       On a graph paper, draw triangle <m>ABC</m> and its image, triangle <m>A'B'C'</m> as shown in the figure below.
                    </p>
                    <image source="rotation-properties.png">
                        <shortdescription></shortdescription>
                    </image>
                </statement>
            </task>
            <task xml:id="auto_3qfewuan">
                <statement>
                    <p xml:id="auto_j7em4rmt">
                        Pick a point on the graph to act as the centre of rotation. Mark this point <m>O</m>
                    </p>
                    <image source="rotation-properties1.png">
                        <shortdescription></shortdescription>
                    </image>
                </statement>
            </task>
            <task xml:id="auto_hnarmom1">
                <statement>
                    <p xml:id="auto_hh3p9pyy">
                        Using a ruler, draw a straight line from point <m>A</m> to <m>O</m> and also from point <m>A'</m> to <m>O</m> as shown below. 
                        Measure the distance <m>OA</m> and <m>OA'</m> and record your results. What do you notice?
                    </p>
                    <image source="rotation-properties2.png">
                        <shortdescription></shortdescription>
                    </image>
                </statement>
            </task>
            <task xml:id="auto_2pef5pm9">
                <statement>
                    <p xml:id="auto_1ik3cn8v">
                        Similarly, draw a straight line from point <m>B</m> to <m>O</m> and also from point <m>B'</m> to <m>O</m>. Measure the distance <m>OB</m> and <m>OB'</m> and record your results. What do you notice?
                    </p>
                    <image source="rotation-properties3.png">
                        <shortdescription></shortdescription>
                    </image>
                </statement>
            </task>
            <task xml:id="auto_3pncczrj">
                <statement>
                    <p xml:id="auto_irzs32qg">
                        Finally, draw a straight line from point <m>C</m> to <m>O</m> and also from point <m>C'</m> to <m>O</m>. Measure the distance <m>OC</m> and <m>OC'</m> and record your results. What do you notice?
                    </p>
                    <image source="rotation-properties4.png">
                        <shortdescription></shortdescription>
                    </image>
                </statement>
            </task>
            <task xml:id="auto_ls02yv5f">
                <statement>
                    <p xml:id="auto_efp9rzmy">
                        Now using a protractor, measure <m>\angle\, AOA'</m>, <m>\angle\, BOB'</m> and <m>\angle\, COC'</m> and record your results. What do you notice?
                    </p>
                </statement>
            </task>
         </activity>
         <figure xml:id="fig-activity-properties-rotation">
            <caption>Interactive Activity: Measuring Properties of Rotation</caption>
            <interactive xml:id="interactive-properties-rotation-act" platform="jsxgraph" width="100%" aspect="1:1" source="jsxgraph/properties-of-rotation-activity.js">
                <slate xml:id="jsxgraph-properties-rotation-act" surface="jsxboard" aspect="1:1"/>
                <instructions xml:id="inst-properties-rotation-act">
                    <p>
                        Follow the steps of your activity using this interactive board! Adjust the angle slider or drag the center of rotation <m>O</m>. 
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        Use the checkboxes at the bottom left to systematically draw the lines from the vertices to the center <m>O</m>. Observe the text calculations at the bottom right to verify that the distance from the object to the center is exactly equal to the distance from the image to the center.
                    </p>
                </instructions>
            </interactive>
        </figure>


        <insight>
            <p xml:id="auto_nn6tdadb">
                The distance <m>AO=A'O</m>, <m>BO=B'O</m> and <m>CO=C'O</m>
            </p>

            <p xml:id="auto_27olt4p1">
                The distance from a point to the centre of rotation is the same as the distance from the image of that point to the centre of rotation.
            </p>

            <p xml:id="auto_zz69scg3">
                <m>\angle\, AOA'=</m> <m>\angle\, BOB'=</m>  <m>\angle\, COC'=90^\circ</m>
            </p>

            <p xml:id="auto_f46cyj6d">
                The angle of rotation is the same for all points in the shape.
            </p>

            <p xml:id="auto_2rqq4ln6">
                In this case, Point <m>O</m> is the centre of rotation and angle <m>90^\circ</m> is the angle of rotation.
            </p>
        
            <p xml:id="auto_fgoo066d">
                <m>\textbf{Note:}</m>
            </p>

            <p xml:id="auto_hernk1gc">
                <ul xml:id="auto_v1m84dko">
                    <li xml:id="auto_z2qtipwa">
                        <p xml:id="auto_6tizep1b">
                            A rotation in the anticlockwise direction is taken to be positive  i.e a rotation of <m>45^\circ</m> anticlockwise is <m>+45^\circ</m>
                        </p>
                    </li>

                    <li xml:id="auto_fakwyobg">
                        <p xml:id="auto_3bwwkixe">
                            A rotation in the clockwise direction is taken to be negative  i.e a rotation of <m>45^\circ</m> clockwise is <m>-45^\circ</m>
                        </p>
                    </li>

                    <li xml:id="auto_2x6j43qe">
                        <p xml:id="auto_j1lbr28e">
                            In general, for a rotation to be completely defined, the centre and angle of rotation must be stated.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ul>
            </p>
        </insight>

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Structured Instruction</title>
        <p>
            <dl>
            <li>
                <title>Suggested Time</title>
                <p>
                    10 minutes
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <title>Objective</title>
                <p>
                    To formalise the key properties and rotation rules.
                </p>
            </li>
            </dl>
        </p>
        <paragraphs>
            <title>Key Properties</title>
            <ol>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        Centre stays fixed.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        Distance from centre preserved (<m>OA = OA'</m>).
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        Angle of rotation same for all points.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        Shape and size preserved (congruent).
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        Orientation preserved (unlike reflection).
                    </p>
                </li>
            </ol>
        </paragraphs>
        <paragraphs>
            <title>Rotation Rules</title>
            <table>
                <title>Rotation Rules about the Origin</title>
                <tabular halign="left">
                    <row header="yes" bottom="minor">
                        <cell>Rotation</cell>
                        <cell>Rule</cell>
                    </row>
                    <row>
                        <cell><m>90°</m> anticlockwise</cell>
                        <cell><m>(x,y) \to (-y, x)</m></cell>
                    </row>
                    <row>
                        <cell><m>180°</m></cell>
                        <cell><m>(x,y) \to (-x, -y)</m></cell>
                    </row>
                    <row>
                        <cell><m>270°</m> anticlockwise / <m>90°</m> clockwise</cell>
                        <cell><m>(x,y) \to (y, -x)</m></cell>
                    </row>
                    <row>
                        <cell><m>360°</m></cell>
                        <cell><m>(x,y) \to (x, y)</m></cell>
                    </row>
                </tabular>
            </table>
        </paragraphs>
        <paragraphs>
            <title>Finding the Centre of Rotation</title>
            <p>
                <alert>Perpendicular Bisector Method:</alert> Draw segment <m>PP'</m>, draw its perpendicular bisector, repeat for <m>QQ'</m>, the intersection is the centre of rotation.
            </p>
            <p>
                <alert>Misconception Alert:</alert> <q>Rotation about the ORIGIN is simpler. Rotation about other centres requires translation first.</q>
            </p>
        </paragraphs>
    </axiom>

        <example xml:id="auto_2ychvh0o">
            <statement>
                <p xml:id="auto_evv5t5q6">
                    
                </p>
                <p xml:id="auto_m4lbxlel"> 
                    The coordinates of the vertices for triangle <m>PQR</m> that can be graphed in the coordinate plane are <m>(-8,-6)</m>, <m>(-2,-6)</m> and <m>(-5,-3)</m>  as shown below. The triangle is rotated through <m>90^\circ</m> in a clockwise direction about the origin to produce triangle <m>P'Q'R'</m>.Copy the figure and draw triangle <m>P'Q'R'</m> 
                </p>

                <figure xml:id="object1">
                    <caption></caption>
                    <image source="object1.png">
                    <shortdescription></shortdescription>
                </image>
                </figure>
            </statement>

            <solution>
                <p xml:id="auto_484h8va6">
                    
                </p>

                <figure xml:id="rotation-90-clockwise">
                    <caption></caption>
                    <image source="rotation-90-clockwise.png">
                    <shortdescription></shortdescription>
                </image>
                </figure>
            </solution>
        </example>
    </introduction>
    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Practice and Application / Elaborate</title>
        <p>
            <dl>
            <li>
                <title>Suggested Time</title>
                <p>
                    10 minutes
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <title>Objective</title>
                <p>
                    To apply rotation rules and verify properties.
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <title>Teacher's Role</title>
                <p>
                    Guide learners through worked examples. Emphasize verifying distances from the centre are preserved. Use tables to organise coordinate calculations.
                </p>
            </li>
            </dl>
        </p>
        <paragraphs>
            <title>Worked Problems</title>
            <p>
                <alert>Problem 1:</alert> Triangle <m>A(1,2)</m>, <m>B(4,2)</m>, <m>C(3,5)</m>. Rotate <m>90°</m> anticlockwise about the origin.
                <m>A'(-2,1)</m>, <m>B'(-2,4)</m>, <m>C'(-5,3)</m>.
                Verify: <m>OA = \sqrt{5}</m>, <m>OA' = \sqrt{5}</m>.
            </p>
            <p>
                <alert>Problem 2:</alert> Rectangle <m>P(1,1)</m>, <m>Q(4,1)</m>, <m>R(4,3)</m>, <m>S(1,3)</m>. Rotate <m>180°</m> about the origin.
                <m>P'(-1,-1)</m>, <m>Q'(-4,-1)</m>, <m>R'(-4,-3)</m>, <m>S'(-1,-3)</m>.
                Verify: <m>OP = \sqrt{2}</m>, <m>OP' = \sqrt{2}</m>.
            </p>
            <p>
                <alert>Problem 3:</alert> Find centre given <m>A(3,1) \to A'(1,-3)</m>, <m>B(5,1) \to B'(1,-5)</m>.
            </p>
            <p>
                Midpoint of <m>AA' = (2,-1)</m>, gradient of <m>AA' = 2</m>, perpendicular gradient <m>= -\frac{1}{2}</m>.
                Perpendicular bisector: <m>y + 1 = -\frac{1}{2}(x - 2)</m> gives <m>y = -\frac{x}{2}</m>.
            </p>
            <p>
                Midpoint of <m>BB' = (3,-2)</m>, gradient of <m>BB' = \frac{3}{2}</m>, perpendicular gradient <m>= -\frac{2}{3}</m>.
                Perpendicular bisector: <m>y + 2 = -\frac{2}{3}(x - 3)</m> gives <m>y = -\frac{2x}{3}</m>.
            </p>
            <p>
                Solving: <m>-\frac{x}{2} = -\frac{2x}{3}</m> gives <m>x = 0</m>, <m>y = 0</m>.
                Centre <m>= (0,0)</m>. Angle: using vectors <m>OA</m> and <m>OA'</m>, <m>\tan \theta</m> gives <m>-90°</m> (clockwise).
            </p>
        </paragraphs>
    </axiom>

    <subsubsection xml:id="subsubsec-centre-and-angle-of-rotation" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
        <title>Centre and Angle of Rotation</title>

        <activity xml:id="auto_hl2bd4ry">
            <statement>
                <p xml:id="auto_1nfdbwmf">
                   <m>\textbf{ Work in pairs.}</m>
                </p>

                <p xml:id="auto_uoml8tcq">
                    <m>\textbf{What you need:}</m> Graph paper, a ruler, a protractor and a pencil
                </p>

                <p xml:id="auto_3xshjnza">
                    <ol xml:id="auto_dv1t51rr">
                        <li xml:id="auto_7gj58g86">
                            <p xml:id="auto_w5igg6kx">
                                On a piece of graph paper draw triangle <m>ABC</m> and its image <m>A'B'C'</m> as shown in the figure below.
                            </p>

                            <image source="centre-angle-of-rotation.png">
                                <shortdescription></shortdescription>
                            </image>
                        </li>

                        <li xml:id="auto_1k1dcrvs">
                            <p xml:id="auto_38tujb9o">
                                Join point <m>A</m> to <m>A'</m> and construct a perpendicular bisector to <m>AA'</m> as shown below;
                            </p>

                            <image source="perpendicular-bisector1.png">
                                <shortdescription></shortdescription>
                            </image>
                        </li>

                        <li xml:id="auto_mtm2nf8p">
                            <p xml:id="auto_sq9kxgui">
                                Similary Join point <m>B</m> to <m>B'</m> and <m>C</m>  to <m>C'</m> and construct a perpendicular bisector to <m>BB'</m> and <m>CC'</m> as shown below;
                            </p>

                            <image source="angle-rotation3.png">
                                <shortdescription></shortdescription>
                            </image>
                        </li>

                        <li xml:id="auto_dz37pclk">
                            <p xml:id="auto_8iz934cr">
                                Now join point <m>O</m> to <m>C'</m> and <m>C</m> and measusure <m>\angle\, COC'</m>
                            </p>
                        </li>

                        <li xml:id="auto_xap8t0pp">
                            <p xml:id="auto_oa9ba9f2">
                                Similary join point <m>O</m> to <m>B'</m> and <m>B</m> and  <m>O</m> to <m>A'</m> and <m>A</m>and measusure <m>\angle\, BOB'</m> and <m>\angle\,AOA'</m>. What do you notice?
                            </p>

                            <image source="centre-angle-of-rotation4.png">
                                <shortdescription></shortdescription>
                            </image>
                        </li>

                        <li xml:id="auto_twt2259s">
                            <p xml:id="auto_ff4a60cn">
                                Share your work with other leaners in class
                            </p>
                        </li>
                    </ol>
                </p>

               
                <p xml:id="auto_qqdkcu6p">
                      <m>\textbf{Key Takeaway}</m>
                </p>

                <p xml:id="auto_lgptlhp5">
                    Triangle <m>A'B'C'</m> is the image of triangle <m>ABC</m> after a rotation.The centre and angle of rotation can be found by drawing the perpendicular bisectors of the lines between two sets of points, <m>C</m> and <m>C'</m> and <m>B</m> and <m>B'</m> or <m>A</m> and <m>A'</m>
                </p>

                    <p xml:id="auto_pxyeuo0v">
                      The point where two perpendicular bisectors intersect is called <m>\textbf{the centre of rotation.}</m> 
                      To find <m>\textbf{ the angle of rotation}</m>, join <m>C'</m> and <m>C</m> to the centre of rotation and measure the angle between these lines.
                </p>

                <p xml:id="auto_ww2x3ici">
                    <m>\angle\, COC'=</m><m>\angle\, BOB'=</m><m>\angle\, AOA'</m>
                </p>

             </statement>
        </activity>
        <figure xml:id="fig-activity-finding-centre">
            <caption>Interactive Activity: Finding the Centre of Rotation</caption>
            <interactive xml:id="interactive-finding-centre-act" platform="jsxgraph" width="100%" aspect="1:1" source="jsxgraph/finding-centre-rotation-activity.js">
                <slate xml:id="jsxgraph-finding-centre-act" surface="jsxboard" aspect="1:1"/>
                <instructions xml:id="inst-finding-centre-act">
                    <p>
                        Use this interactive tool to follow the geometric construction steps for finding a center of rotation. 
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        Click the checkboxes at the bottom left in order (from 1 to 5). Notice how the perpendicular bisector of the line joining corresponding points (<m>AA'</m>) and the perpendicular bisector of (<m>BB'</m>) perfectly intersect. That exact point of intersection is your centre of rotation!
                    </p>
                </instructions>
            </interactive>
        </figure>
        <example xml:id="auto_uzwpvdn2">
            <statement>
                <p xml:id="auto_jc8zp0z5">
                    
                </p>
                <p xml:id="auto_aju2pewj">
                    In the figures below, the triangle <m>X'Y'Z'</m> is the image of triangle <m>XYZ</m> after rotation. Find the centre and angle of rotation
                </p>

                <image source="example-centre-angle-of-rotation.png">
                    <shortdescription></shortdescription>
                </image>
            </statement>

            <solution> 
                <p xml:id="auto_v56nnfwp">
                    In order to determine the centre and angle of rotation we have to follow the following steps:
                </p>

                <p xml:id="auto_xkb3k2ta">
                    <ol xml:id="auto_gml7ws2r">
                        <li xml:id="auto_0qblyx5n">
                            <p xml:id="auto_1d3jkwzv">
                                Join point <m>Z</m> to <m>Z'</m> and construct a perpendicular bisector to <m>ZZ''</m> as shown below
                            </p>

                            <image source="centre-angle-of-rotation3.png">
                                <shortdescription></shortdescription>
                            </image>
                        </li>

                        <li xml:id="auto_0deqjhrc">
                            <p xml:id="auto_c9vppdn2">
                                Also join point <m>Y</m> to <m>Y'</m> and construct a perpendicular bisector to <m>YY'</m> as shown below. Mark the point of intersection of perpendicular bisectors <m>O</m>
                            </p>

                            <image source="centre-angle-of-rotation5.png">
                                <shortdescription></shortdescription>
                            </image>
                        </li>

                        <li xml:id="auto_rcquzz1r">
                            <p xml:id="auto_myzj9a3c">
                                Similary you can join <m>X</m> to <m>X'</m> and construct a perpendicular bisector to <m>XX'</m>
                            </p>

                            <p xml:id="auto_2jzzhjck">
                                <m>\textbf{Note}</m> You can use only two points.
                            </p>

                            <p xml:id="auto_e8s77etr">
                               The point where perpendicular bisectors intersect is the centre of rotation.
                            </p>
                        </li>

                        <li xml:id="auto_maspwi3x">
                            <p xml:id="auto_pxi62s6y">
                                Now join <m>Z</m> and <m>Z'</m> to the centre of rotation <m>O</m>. Measure <m>\angle, ZOZ'</m> using a protractor. 
                            </p>

                            <image source="centre-angle-of-rotation7.png">
                                <shortdescription></shortdescription>
                            </image>
                        </li>
                    </ol>
                </p>

                <p xml:id="auto_rl066hif">
                    Centre of rotation <m>=(-1,1)</m>
                </p>

                <p xml:id="auto_wg3mayom">
                    Angle of rotation <m>=-160^\circ</m> since rotation is done in a clockwise direction
                </p>

            </solution>
        </example>

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Assessment / Evaluate</title>
        <p>
            <dl>
            <li>
                <title>Suggested Time</title>
                <p>
                    5 minutes
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <title>Objective</title>
                <p>
                    To formatively assess individual learner understanding.
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <title>Learning Experience</title>
                <p>
                    Learners independently complete a short assessment task (select from the exercises below).
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <title>Teacher's Role</title>
                <p>
                    Collect and review the exit tickets to gauge learner understanding and identify any common misconceptions that need to be addressed in the next lesson.
                </p>
            </li>
            </dl>
        </p>
        <paragraphs>
            <title>Answer Key</title>
            <p>
                <alert>Q1.</alert> Properties of rotation (3 properties): Distance preserved, shape/size preserved, angle same for all points.
            </p>
            <p>
                <alert>Q2.</alert> <m>P(3,4)</m> rotated <m>90°</m> anticlockwise about <m>O</m>: <m>P'(-4,3)</m>.
            </p>
            <p>
                <alert>Q3.</alert> <m>A(2,0) \to A'(0,2)</m>. What rotation? <m>90°</m> anticlockwise about origin.
            </p>
            <p>
                <alert>Q4.</alert> Why is shape preserved? Every point moves the same angle, distance from centre unchanged.
            </p>
            <p>
                <alert>Q5.</alert> <m>P(1,0) \to P'(-1,0)</m>. Angle? <m>180°</m>.
            </p>
        </paragraphs>
    </axiom>

        <exercises xml:id="exercises-centre-and-angle-of-rotation">

        <exercise xml:id="auto_7945vncx">
            <statement>
                <p xml:id="auto_khc1yqpd">
                    In the figure below, rectangle <m>A'B'C'D'</m> is the image of rectangle <m>ABCD</m> under a rotation, centre <m>O</m>
                </p>

                <image source="image-object-rectangle.png">
                    <shortdescription></shortdescription>
                </image>

                <p xml:id="auto_2kequnq4">
                   (a). By construction,find and label the centre <m>O</m> of roration.
                </p>

                <p xml:id="auto_jywnm2jg">
                    (b) Determine the angle of rotation.
                </p>
            </statement>
        </exercise>
            
        </exercises>

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Differentiation</title>

        <table>
            <title>Differentiation</title>
            <tabular halign="left">
                <row header="yes" bottom="minor">
                    <cell>Learner Group</cell>
                    <cell>Strategy &amp; Learning Experience</cell>
                    <cell></cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell>Struggling Learners (Support)</cell>
                    <cell>
                        <line><alert>Scaffolding:</alert> Use physical rotation (tracing paper on pin). Start with <m>180°</m> only. Provide grid paper. Colour-code object/image. Use a step-by-step rotation checklist.</line>
                    </cell>
                    <cell></cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell>On-Level Learners (Core)</cell>
                    <cell>
                        <line>Complete all three rotation rules. Find centre using perpendicular bisectors. Verify properties by measurement.</line>
                    </cell>
                    <cell></cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell>Advanced Learners (Challenge)</cell>
                    <cell>
                        <line><alert>Extended Learning Experience:</alert> Rotation about a point other than the origin. Composition of rotations. Prove rotation preserves distance. Rotation matrices.</line>
                    </cell>
                    <cell></cell>
                </row>
            </tabular>
        </table>

        <paragraphs>
            <title>Extension Activities</title>
            <ol>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        Rotate <m>\triangle (1,2),(3,2),(2,4)</m> by <m>90°</m> CW about <m>(1,1)</m>.
                        Translate to origin: <m>(0,1),(2,1),(1,3)</m>.
                        Apply <m>(x,y) \to (y,-x)</m>: <m>(1,0),(1,-2),(3,-1)</m>.
                        Translate back: <m>(2,1),(2,-1),(4,0)</m>.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        Two successive <m>90°</m> rotations about different centres. First about <m>O(0,0)</m>: <m>(1,0) \to (0,1)</m>. Then about <m>(2,0)</m>: translate <m>(0,1) \to (-2,1)</m>, rotate <m>\to (1,2)</m>, translate back <m>\to (3,2)</m>. What single transformation? Investigate.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        Prove: composition of rotation <m>\alpha</m> then <m>\beta</m> about the same centre <m>= </m> rotation <m>\alpha + \beta</m>.
                    </p>
                </li>
            </ol>
        </paragraphs>
    </axiom>
        
    </subsubsection>
    


